        "category": "Revisions",
        "theory": "# Quiz 1 Review: Bringing it all Together\n\nThis module reviews the core concepts we've covered so far to make sure you are ready for any challenge!\n\n---\n\n## Foundations Checklist\n\nBefore moving on, make sure you can explain these like a 5th grader:\n- **ML:** A computer learning from experience without being told exactly what to do.\n- **Supervised Learning:** Learning with a teacher (labeled data).\n- **Unsupervised Learning:** Learning by finding patterns on your own.\n- **Loss Function:** The \"Scoreboard\" that tells the computer how many mistakes it made.\n\n---\n\n## Math Quick-Ref\n\n| Concept | The \"Quick\" Version |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Derivative** | The slope of the hill. |\n| **Gradient** | The magic compass pointing uphill. |\n| **Matrix** | An organized box of numbers. |\n| **Eigenvector** | A direction that stays straight when stretched. |\n| **PCA** | Finding the best angle to take a photo. |\n\n---\n\n## High-Level Summary\n\nMachine Learning is just a giant cycle:\n1. **Gather Data** (Linear Algebra)\n2. **Guess a Model** (Functions & Geometry)\n3. **Measure the Error** (Loss Functions)\n4. **Fix the Model** (Calculus & Optimization)\n5. **Repeat!**\n\n---\n\n## Final Review Question\n\n**Question:** If you want to find the relationship between \"Price\" and \"Size,\" but your data is a messy cloud of points, which mathematical tool should you use to find the **best-fit line**?\n\n**Solution:**\nYou should use **Least Squares Optimization** (Category 03). It will find the line that makes the \"Total Square Error\" as small as possible.\n\n> [!TIP]\n> You've made it through the foundations! You now have the mathematical superpowers needed to build and understand the world's most advanced AI systems.\n",
